          "line": 492,
          "severity": "medium",
          "category": "correctness",
          "title": "hailSchemes fallback uses ConcernLevel.LOW but label and intent are 'Unclassified'",
          "body": "hailSchemes() defines its own fallback bucket with label='Unclassified', ordinal=-1, color='#999999CC' \u2014 identical to NO_MATCH_FALLBACK in every field except concernLevel, which is ConcernLevel.LOW instead of ConcernLevel.UNCLASSIFIED. All other schemes that need this same fallback reuse NO_MATCH_FALLBACK directly. The duplicate inline bucket is also not DRY. Fix: replace the entire inline fallback with 'fallback = NO_MATCH_FALLBACK'.",
          "confidence": "high"
        },
        {
          "file": "service/shared/src/test/kotlin/co/arqu/georiskservice/shared/classification/ClassificationSchemesTest.kt",
          "line": 145,
          "severity": "low",
          "category": "style",
          "title": "FallbackConstants inner class closing brace is missing indentation",
          "body": "The closing brace for the FallbackConstants @Nested inner class (line 145) has zero indentation instead of the 4-space indentation used for all other inner class closing braces in the file. This is inconsistent with the file's formatting convention. Fix: indent the closing brace of FallbackConstants to 4 spaces.",
          "confidence": "high"
        },
        {
          "file": "service/lambda/src/test/kotlin/co/arqu/georiskservice/api/DescribeFeatureSetGroupsTest.kt",
          "line": 175,
          "severity": "low",
          "category": "correctness",
          "title": "buildFsg for NOAA-Hail passes riskType=Hail but the canonical risk type is Wind",
          "body": "Line 175: buildFsg(\"NOAA-Hail\", \"Hail\") uses riskType=\"Hail\". The canonical mapping in FSG_RISK_TYPES (FeatureSetGroup.kt) assigns NOAA-Hail to \"Wind\". Using the wrong risk type causes fsg.relevanceProximity() to log a warning and return the 1.0-mile default instead of the configured 10.0-mile Wind proximity. The test only asserts on classification scheme structure so no assertion fails today, but the wrong riskType means the test is exercising a code path that would not occur in production. Fix: change riskType to \"Wind\" to match the canonical FSG registration.",
          "confidence": "high"
        }
      ]
    },
